  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Commission Recommendation 2003/361/EC">
  <data key="d0">Commission Recommendation 2003/361/EC</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Commission Recommendation 2003/361/EC outlines definitions and criteria for classifying micro, small, and medium-sized enterprises within the Union.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e2d13a59890e903c4e56162458f272ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018972</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Micro, Small, and Medium-Sized Enterprises">
  <data key="d0">Micro, Small, and Medium-Sized Enterprises</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Micro, small, and medium-sized enterprises are categorized businesses within the Union that may benefit from specific regulations regarding data processing and protection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-e2d13a59890e903c4e56162458f272ab</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018972</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Directive 95/46/EC">
  <data key="d0">Directive 95/46/EC</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Directive 95/46/EC is a European directive aimed at establishing minimum standards for the protection of personal data and privacy. It was designed to harmonize the protection of natural persons concerning the processing of personal data across the European Union. The directive served as a foundational regulation that outlined specific obligations for organizations, including the requirement to notify supervisory authorities about personal data processing activities.

As a piece of legislation, Directive 95/46/EC laid down a comprehensive legal framework for data protection within the European Union, providing essential guidelines to ensure individuals' rights regarding their personal information were safeguarded. However, it is important to note that Directive 95/46/EC has since been repealed by Regulation (EU) 2016/679, known commonly as the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which has established more stringent data protection measures and requirements.

Overall, Directive 95/46/EC played a critical role in shaping the landscape of data protection law in Europe, serving as a precursor to the more robust regulations set forth in the GDPR.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-2cbf3f86a25d11cd5d991d79db9a221a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89bcf919dc1ff2d224ffc9b6e042a2c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-76c97638c70c32faaac95c378d456ab2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-58a23170492ef728683ec4aa9e03ccb4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b39c0bb45bd2a8849aa7e9bcb8c9d4a1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9403aaca1e6e92e51844c1b1175b373b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-66f1f525b011c8f0bfb14ba0891419e3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5ab41d6ec0d1446be5ba58c1ab5b423c</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018972</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Article 31">
  <data key="d0">Article 31</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Article 31 refers to the section discussing cooperation with supervisory authority regarding data processing and management responsibilities.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 31 sets forth the requirements related to notified bodies, including their establishment, independence, and operational standards.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 31 lays down the requirements that conformity assessment bodies must satisfy.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 31 refers to a specific section regarding compliance in a regulatory context.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 31 includes requirements and obligations for notified bodies in regulatory compliance.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-47177763646868a685685b7567bea40f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b45385ec456bd2744fcc58cd02368fc0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fe99ac2ad30ad5f2f6c6c5e2e23456e9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1d997baeb2a2ac2118ac1e3e19dfcf16&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-926dc457d536779e13715d0b813c320d</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019203</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Article 32">
  <data key="d0">Article 32</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Article 32 outlines the security requirements for processing personal data, including implementation of technical and organizational measures.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 32 discusses the presumption of conformity with requirements relating to notified bodies and their compliance with harmonised standards.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-47177763646868a685685b7567bea40f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-78ea54ae6ffd2850256fb7ad037b8474</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019211</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Article 33">
  <data key="d0">Article 33</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Article 33 details the notification procedure for personal data breaches to the supervisory authority, emphasizing timely reporting and necessary information.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 33 covers the specifics regarding subsidiaries of notified bodies and the subcontracting of assessment tasks.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 33 further clarifies obligations and requirements for notified bodies in different paragraphs.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-47177763646868a685685b7567bea40f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b45385ec456bd2744fcc58cd02368fc0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-78ea54ae6ffd2850256fb7ad037b8474</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019203</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Personal Data Breach">
  <data key="d0">Personal Data Breach</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A Personal Data Breach refers to incidents where personal data is improperly processed or exposed, potentially leading to damage.&lt;SEP&gt;A personal data breach refers to incidents where personal data is compromised, potentially resulting in various detrimental effects to natural persons.&lt;SEP&gt;A personal data breach involves unauthorized access, destruction, loss, or alteration of personal data.&lt;SEP&gt;A personal data breach occurs when there is unauthorized access to or disclosure of personal data, leading to potential risks for the rights and freedoms of individuals.&lt;SEP&gt;A Personal Data Breach refers to an event where personal data is accessed, compromised, or disclosed without authorization.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-47177763646868a685685b7567bea40f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89bcf919dc1ff2d224ffc9b6e042a2c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3ce3387b9f0e9256cf8b0a10e0726f37&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7d95ad85f86f6e4a4771e8f92b0cbf27&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7e5e9be572ec001588771fa74ce45258</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018973</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Data Protection Officer">
  <data key="d0">Data Protection Officer</data>
  <data key="d1">person</data>
  <data key="d2">The Data Protection Officer is a role within an organization responsible for overseeing data protection strategies and compliance.&lt;SEP&gt;The Data Protection Officer is a designated individual responsible for overseeing data protection practices and compliance within an organization.&lt;SEP&gt;Data Protection Officer is a role responsible for overseeing data protection compliance within an organization.&lt;SEP&gt;The data protection officer is an individual designated to ensure compliance with data protection laws and to act as a point of contact for data subjects and regulatory authorities.&lt;SEP&gt;The data protection officer is a designated individual responsible for overseeing data protection activities and advising on compliance and risks.&lt;SEP&gt;The Data Protection Officer is designated to ensure compliance with data protection laws and is involved in tasks related to personal data protection.&lt;SEP&gt;The Data Protection Officer is responsible for ensuring compliance with data protection regulations and must be involved in data protection issues.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-47177763646868a685685b7567bea40f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-db7bcd6a42a9c26ced1d71444d109dff&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e144d059e01c4df4d2fdb9406d31751d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8252fb4b704db3adac7bfb7714d3b70f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df28c0bb060b598df163cc06bf49d0e9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4f71c70521bc1935b4a077373428f4b1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8907f0fe9fc1b981b8c734b5cbf9008</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018973</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Article 40">
  <data key="d0">Article 40</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Article 40 pertains to the establishment and approval of codes of conduct for data controllers and processors, playing a crucial role in the evaluation of data processing impacts. This article emphasizes the importance of adhering to these approved codes, which facilitate compliance with data processing requirements and contribute to the effective application of data protection regulations.

Furthermore, Article 40 outlines the conditions under which organizations may be accredited to monitor compliance with a given code of conduct, ensuring that these codes are not only developed but also effectively implemented and enforced. It addresses the issuance of opinions and the approval process for draft codes of conduct, highlighting the collaborative framework necessary for developing these guidelines.

In addition to its focus on compliance and standards, Article 40 discusses harmonized standards specifically related to artificial intelligence (AI) systems. It defines the necessary specifications that could provide a presumption of conformity for these systems, aligning them with established data protection norms.

Overall, Article 40 serves as a comprehensive framework for developing and adhering to codes of conduct in data processing, while also addressing the evolving standards required for AI systems. This multifaceted approach ensures that data protection regulations remain relevant and effective in an increasingly digital landscape.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-47177763646868a685685b7567bea40f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-18dac2bb6a1be4d5442954b82a769ffd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e09a4cc6243398f5e32d65a6312bd87&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-274264435e41f5d230030900b38f8c35&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c8907f0fe9fc1b981b8c734b5cbf9008&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65949aed6696e22716296aea9c7eb380&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6fb6a4af737980e04056c2522ea213fe&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9a54b012266e9b9c7302fce6d400f583&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-926dc457d536779e13715d0b813c320d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-413f3509ccce7d84f0a2044eb12be69f</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019198</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Article 42">
  <data key="d0">Article 42</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Article 42 discusses the use of an approved certification mechanism as a means of demonstrating compliance with data protection regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 42 addresses certification processes and mechanisms for data protection compliance by controllers and processors.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 42 outlines the issuance of certifications and criteria for certification.&lt;SEP&gt;Article 42 addresses certification mechanisms and seals for data protection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-47177763646868a685685b7567bea40f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-18dac2bb6a1be4d5442954b82a769ffd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9e09a4cc6243398f5e32d65a6312bd87&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6fb6a4af737980e04056c2522ea213fe</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018973</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Processing Operations">
  <data key="d0">Processing Operations</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Processing Operations involve any operation or set of operations performed on personal data, including collection, storage, and analysis.&lt;SEP&gt;Processing operations refer to actions involving personal data that carry a high risk, which may require consultation with the supervisory authority prior to processing.&lt;SEP&gt;Processing operations refer to the activities involved in handling personal data as outlined by the regulation.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3dec771ee61059f33dea3999f6d5facd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-89bcf919dc1ff2d224ffc9b6e042a2c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-224ac909847d6dc3f9484ef626d8ecd2</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018974</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Large-Scale Processing">
  <data key="d0">Large-Scale Processing</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Large-Scale Processing involves handling a significant volume of personal data, which may heighten the risks to data subjects' rights and freedoms.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3dec771ee61059f33dea3999f6d5facd</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018974</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Biometric Data">
  <data key="d0">Biometric Data</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Biometric Data refers to a category of personal data that is processed specifically for the purpose of unique identification or authentication of individuals. This type of data encompasses physiological and behavioral characteristics, which allow for the identification and categorization of natural persons. Biometric Data is derived from biological traits such as facial features, fingerprints, and other unique physical or behavioral markers.

The classification of Biometric Data is significant in the context of data regulations, as it requires specific handling to ensure compliance with legal frameworks. This is particularly relevant given that the processing of such data involves technical means that can affect individuals. As a result, the management of Biometric Data must address privacy concerns and regulatory requirements effectively.

Biometric Data not only serves for identification but also plays a critical role in access control, enabling secure authentication methods in various systems. It includes unique identifiers that are closely linked to individual physical characteristics, making it a sensitive category of personal data. The use of Biometric Data is also increasingly integrated into artificial intelligence systems, which can process this information to facilitate identification and categorization in diverse applications. 

Overall, Biometric Data is essential for modern identification technologies and carries significant implications for personal privacy and data protection.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3dec771ee61059f33dea3999f6d5facd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4816e09d93a70dec7bd3be2be787d180&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cc7a45c7f8eea9ab9297b5839c19c2a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b1184185c4bc8012fe969516fa45f07b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7e5e9be572ec001588771fa74ce45258&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aebf35e601756ab37e5d744110a4c050&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-62c64f05f2da893351ea92b9eac1c889&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6243f0a255a83e57f7b7de8b0b878719&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9238afdc9781d2e524a5550b3c165bed&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-358eb1d0b0f35e665a7b23702159cfd5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-22dcb6c71a1828d1166aad9d5a7cac19&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-df495629e0a16630b58b47ba83c27efa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-00803764d58d840979922e38d1dc555c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e14a05a776d89b0f172b0c5789b0936</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019169</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Special Categories of Personal Data">
  <data key="d0">Special Categories of Personal Data</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Special categories of personal data require higher protection and are used under specific conditions as outlined in the Regulation.&lt;SEP&gt;Special Categories of Personal Data refer to sensitive information that requires higher levels of protection under data protection regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;Special categories of personal data include sensitive information such as racial or ethnic origin, political opinions, and health-related data, which are subject to stricter regulations.&lt;SEP&gt;Special Categories of Personal Data are certain data types outlined in specific European regulations.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-3dec771ee61059f33dea3999f6d5facd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cc7a45c7f8eea9ab9297b5839c19c2a3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c09ea8bbba955df15eafbe1da5facb38&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-aebf35e601756ab37e5d744110a4c050</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019165</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Complaint Submission Form">
  <data key="d0">Complaint Submission Form</data>
  <data key="d1">artifact</data>
  <data key="d2">The Complaint Submission Form is a tool provided by the Supervisory Authority to facilitate the submission of complaints by data subjects.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-8bb97fdc90c81e778311b34e1a2883b2</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773018974</data>
