<node id="Regulation (EU) No 182/2011">
  <data key="d0">Regulation (EU) No 182/2011</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Regulation (EU) No 182/2011 provides the framework for the exercise of implementing powers conferred on the Commission.&lt;SEP&gt;Regulation (EU) No 182/2011 outlines the committee procedure within the European Union.&lt;SEP&gt;Regulation (EU) No 182/2011 outlines the rules and principles governing the control mechanisms for the Commission's implementing powers by Member States.&lt;SEP&gt;Regulation (EU) No 182/2011 sets out the procedural rules and framework for adopting EU legislation and is referenced in the context of the committee procedure.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-58a23170492ef728683ec4aa9e03ccb4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b39c0bb45bd2a8849aa7e9bcb8c9d4a1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f5283f6c8ea50d5bcac79684f773610&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6a7c04a6e62adc17c47006b55b3e8bce</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019201</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Article 5">
  <data key="d0">Article 5</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">Article 5 encompasses multiple distinct subjects across various legislative frameworks within the European Union. 

Firstly, Article 5 highlights fundamental principles regarding the processing of personal data, asserting that such handling must be lawful, fair, and transparent to adequately protect the rights of data subjects. This is a critical component of data protection regulations aimed at ensuring that individuals' information is managed responsibly.

Secondly, in the context of Regulation (EU) No 182/2011, Article 5 pertains specifically to the committee procedure outlined in the documentation, which governs how the European institutions engage with one another in legislative processes.

Additionally, Article 5 relates to the principle of subsidiarity within the EU framework. This principle ensures that decisions are made as closely as possible to the citizen, allowing for intervention only at the EU level when objectives cannot be sufficiently achieved by member states alone.

Furthermore, Article 5 addresses the regulation of artificial intelligence (AI) by delineating certain practices that are prohibited, including manipulative or deceptive techniques that may exploit individuals. It establishes compliance requirements for operators of high-risk AI systems, outlining standards necessary for their deployment and requiring appropriate evaluation to ensure adherence to safety and ethical guidelines.

It also emphasizes the supervisory role of the Commission in overseeing compliance with these prohibitions and requirements regarding AI practices, further ensuring that harmful techniques are mitigated.

In summary, Article 5 is a multi-faceted regulation that spans personal data protection, legislative procedures, principles of subsidiarity, and the oversight of AI practices, all aimed at promoting lawful and ethical standards within the European Union.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-58a23170492ef728683ec4aa9e03ccb4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9355b1cd3c48988b8332485ef99af2c3&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6f379f07f844b3112cd145a56e02874b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9a54b012266e9b9c7302fce6d400f583&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-38cdce9b64b40ba40d6acb529d375787&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7f5283f6c8ea50d5bcac79684f773610&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-382f1c7a3c02bab4bf3bee2d03cc7e1f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b084b4b20e358aaf88a17e35cc6da65d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6a7c04a6e62adc17c47006b55b3e8bce</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019186</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
