</node>
<node id="Serious Incident">
  <data key="d0">Serious Incident</data>
  <data key="d1">concept</data>
  <data key="d2">A serious incident involves malfunctioning AI systems that cause significant harm or disruption, as defined in the regulation.&lt;SEP&gt;A Serious Incident refers to significant occurrences relating to high-risk AI systems that must be reported to regulatory authorities when they are identified.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4b86ca29202de00c1292db00c1efa4b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f763b444522d2da4e393e2f999f53812</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019171</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="National Competent Authorities">
  <data key="d0">National Competent Authorities</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">National Competent Authorities are regulatory bodies designated within each Member State, tasked with overseeing compliance and enforcing regulations pertaining to high-risk Artificial Intelligence (AI) systems. Their primary responsibility is to ensure that AI providers adhere to established requirements and confirm their risk assessments, thus maintaining a high standard of safety and accountability in the deployment of AI technologies.

These authorities are also responsible for receiving and reviewing the EU declaration of conformity for high-risk AI systems. This process is crucial as it helps to verify that the AI systems meet the necessary compliance standards before they are allowed to operate within the market. Additionally, National Competent Authorities play a fundamental role in monitoring and enforcing compliance with AI regulations within their jurisdictions, ensuring that the implementation of these systems adheres to governmental policies and public safety standards.

In addition to compliance oversight, these authorities supervise the establishment and operation of AI regulatory sandboxes, which are controlled environments where new AI technologies can be tested under regulatory supervision. This initiative promotes innovation while maintaining safeguards against potential risks posed by emerging AI technologies.

National Competent Authorities are bound by confidentiality obligations as they operate, which ensures that sensitive information is handled properly during the assessment and regulatory processes. Furthermore, they provide guidance on the implementation of regulations relating to AI systems, assisting stakeholders in navigating the complexities of compliance and regulatory requirements.

Overall, National Competent Authorities serve a critical role in ensuring that high-risk AI systems are developed and deployed responsibly, thereby fostering a safe and innovative AI landscape within their respective jurisdictions.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-663826fe1821a9ef057cd84da3b741a8&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3ca50c2792c184b300a7d258f980e38c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b45385ec456bd2744fcc58cd02368fc0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f0714fdb65a0577bc4493dcb81d0a915&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cf7d18a6020405fb3429834a129e7cd0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-546a0f6bb154d36417ac57e86137b45d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-ccdea28ee93cb8cfdf2099776ddcb591&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-b28096d582da2417ada6ecd24c88d994&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-cfd6bb7a9801a10b9d2b6a706f0d919d</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
  <data key="d5">1773019171</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Non-Personal Data">
  <data key="d0">Non-Personal Data</data>
  <data key="d1">data</data>
  <data key="d2">Non-personal data refers to data that does not pertain to identified or identifiable individuals.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-f4b86ca29202de00c1292db00c1efa4b</data>
  <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
